&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; I just downloaded and looked at their code. They have a fatal, 
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&gt;from 
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; my perspective, flaw. Namely, to generate events against the 
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; components they create a Java level event and post it to the 
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&gt;event 
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&gt; &gt; &gt; queue like so: 
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&gt; &gt; 
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&gt; &gt; I think the lesson here is that testing a GUI framework has 
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&gt;completely 
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&gt; &gt; different needs from testing a GUI application. Having tried to use 
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&gt; &gt; java.awt.Robot to test an application, I prefer the style of 
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&gt;jfcunit. 
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&gt; &gt; 
